{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586641"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:36:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:36:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15085"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15085"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.89,0,0.06,0,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67902"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7773"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15085"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53367"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18975"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67902"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man with chronic kidney disease has an estimated glomerular filtration rate of 45 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u003E90). He has hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His medicines include perindopril, amlodipine, metformin and empagliflozin. His blood pressure is 148/92 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following lifestyle modifications is most likely to improve blood pressure control?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Combined aerobic and resistance training","High protein diet","Carbohydrate restriction","Increased calcium intake","Vitamin D supplementation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with chronic kidney disease (CKD) and poorly controlled hypertension would benefit most from \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombined aerobic and resistance training\u003C/strong\u003E. Regular exercise has been shown to significantly improve blood pressure control in patients with CKD who are not on dialysis, while also improving cardiovascular fitness, muscle strength, and quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh protein diet\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended in CKD as it may accelerate disease progression\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarbohydrate restriction\u003C/strong\u003E alone has not been shown to significantly improve blood pressure in CKD patients\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased calcium intake\u003C/strong\u003E, while important in CKD patients, does not directly improve blood pressure control\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary in CKD due to altered metabolism, but is not a primary intervention for blood pressure control\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important lifestyle modifications include sodium restriction, maintaining a healthy weight, smoking cessation, and limiting alcohol intake.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Regular physical activity, including both aerobic and resistance training, improves blood pressure control in chronic kidney disease.","Dietary sodium restriction is a key lifestyle modification for blood pressure control in chronic kidney disease.","High protein diets should be avoided in chronic kidney disease as they may accelerate disease progression."],"references":["Lancaster KJ. Dietary treatment of blood pressure in kidney disease. Adv Chronic Kidney Dis. 2004 Apr;11(2):217-21. doi: 10.1053/j.arrt.2004.01.007. PMID: 15216494.","Kramer H. Diet and Chronic Kidney Disease. Adv Nutr. 2019 Nov 1;10(Suppl_4):S367-S379. doi: 10.1093/advances/nmz011. PMID: 31728497; PMCID: PMC6855949.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53367"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15085"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53367"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:26:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:28:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7773"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67902"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"ty